## Rear Panel Description

The rear panel of the Sonozap piezo generator contains a BNC connector, 95 /2 65 VAC Input power,
On/Off Switch and DB 9 connector for programing and external control. Changing the status of this
feature can be found in the menu. A pull up resistor is internal to the circuit and is not needed. An open
circuit is adequate.

**Operating the Sonozap Atomizer generator:**

Attach the BNC cable assembly, that came with your unit, to the back of the generator. Make sure that
the transducer that came with your unit is also attached.

Plug in the 95-265 VAC power cord that came with your unit. Assure the power outlet is properly wired
and grounded.

Turn the power switch at the rear panel, ON. A splash screen will pop-up showing the company name
a software revision level and serial number.

The display at this point should show the Sonozap Atomizer name followed by PWR: OFF.

The Sonozap Atomizer generator was pre calibrated from the factory. Press the On/Off button located
on the front panel. Slowly increase the power to the probe with the up arrow. At this point it is difficult
to determine whether the unit is on or off. To determine if the power is on, one can **lightly** touch the
end of the transducer tip. When this is done a slight vibration should be felt. If liquid is on the tip of the
probe, it will begin to agitate, until the power is high enough to atomize the liquid.


## Ultrasonic Atomizer Operation

Connect your fluid source to the back of the transducer with a 1 /8 inch swage-lock fitting. Before
pumping, have power to the probe on, and bar graph should be at 50 % power. Slowly pump the fluid
through the probe. As the fluid reaches the tip end, it should atomize into droplets. Controlling both
the power level and flow rate for a given liquid needs to be adjusted for best results. To complete
spraying, disable pump then the atomizer nozzle

**Note** : If the transducer is used to spray oils, it might be necessary to dilute them for best results. Not
all higher viscosity liquids will atomize. Molecular structure, viscosity, surface tension and density play
a role in the ability to atomize and the particle distribution data that can be measured.

**Atomizer should be operated at full power only when high flows are used, excessive heating
could occur with probes over 13 0 kHz using little or no liquid flow. Low flows usually require
low power levels for fine sprays.**

**If the atomizer frequency goes down about 100 Hz in eight to ten seconds, this is a sign of
beginning to overheat the probe. Adjust power and flow rate accordingly to keep frequency
basically steady.**

**If the application requires high power low flow rate, proper cooling should be provided to
keep atomizer case at 150 degrees F. Atomizer nozzle can be ordered with cooling ports, add
CP at end of P/N.**

If atomizer nozzle does not operate, liquid inside can be loading the device. Blow out liquid, energize
probe, begin liquid flow. To return, stop liquid flow, disable energy to probe.

Excessive heating may be a sign of poor operation, reduce power if necessary.

Atomizer generator will track the frequency of the probe during operation, while heating. If the user
switches probes or shuts off generator. Turning on again the generator will assume it is operating at
room temperature and probe may not operate correctly.

Over pumping fluids through the probe will cause droplets to not be fully atomized. Reduce the flow rate
if necessary.

Over powering the probe will cause liquid to be thrown off the tip in large droplets. Reduce power level
until uniform atomization is achieved. Use a smooth flowing pump for best results.

Do not mount any fixtures or load to the vibrating tip. This will cause the atomizer to under perform.

Mounting can be best achieved by mounting to the case.


